Inflation in Europe has derailed on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, said the European Community's Statistics Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only indicated 3 percent, said Bloomberg.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the policy interest rate by saying that the decline in interest, with the growth of commodity prices and the fall in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must dissuade" inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this subject at a later stage.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area took off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market ratings have increased by 88 per cent and soya prices have also reached their highest since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world price of oil rose by 52 per cent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3-4 months, the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup points to government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly at the beginning of December. Thus since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For faithful voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two thirds (71 per cent) against the support of a fifth (20 per cent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is two percent throughout the population.
Of the faithful voters, some went to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 per cent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate compared to the previous low point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious was never so high, it amounted to 41 per cent and, according to 46 per cent, the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population foresees a worsening and only one-tenth foresees an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 per cent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup surveys, felt that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or have a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 per cent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 per cent trust the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that discontent with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office after the riots last October, at present this rate is only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believes that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 per cent of respondents replied that they would certainly vote and the 20 per cent additional said that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election next Sunday", only 55 per cent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be without doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to higher education fees, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who have expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters, respectively, would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stays.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent last year, the difference being that this year the rate of VAT did not increase.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, an increase of value well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flown away" in the grocery stores last December, no longer increased sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that the items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 forints, at a minimum, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey fillet, nuts and poppy rose sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) data, but at Auchan, bread of only 1 kilo to 139 forints was found.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forints the bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 per cent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 per cent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket with this year's cheapest basket, we see a difference of 12 per cent while the difference between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive basket is 21 per cent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, although the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has made trade perplexed, hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, it risks losing a big profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the rate of VAT, the increase in the daily basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and prices at the lowest were also up 1,284 forints.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items increased by more than 30 per cent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some essential supplies, the Institute of Statistics has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by barely more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the evidence, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get acceptance of the sharp price increase also by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-storage foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important tails formed at the crates of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased abruptly.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less in the provinces, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred at the same location.
The injured in a serious car accident came out of the hospital but shortly after he had to return because of an MRSA infection, and since then the doctors have not been able to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Medical Officer of the National Epidemiology Centre.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e., by methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as anginas, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacterium that will proliferate rapidly in bad hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacteria can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, small weights or with a weakened body.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Above all, we must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only where we are not looking for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the health care staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they carry MRSA, however infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not in mode
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not conducive to preventing the development and proliferation of multi-drug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and seniors' homes, hospitals should monitor in-patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases occur only if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the Chief Medical Officer of the Epidemiological Centre.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian directives for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, significant gaps are detected in hospitals as well in this area.
The MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemics, patients should be at least 1.5 metres away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable way or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why this infection is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of ASM.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-drug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who was responsible for a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness.
The official finding concerning the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was drawn up.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has resigned from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led in a state of drunkenness or stunned, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative observation was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the 22nd district police station crushed a 55-year-old man who was facing him when he shot, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos Street in the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being taken to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned his position and applied for his retirement because, according to the police, this accident greatly upset him.
The investigation into this case is carried out by the Public Prosecutor's Office in Budapest.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
EUR 400 million additional for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of EUR 400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit contract worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties.This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The agreement on the appropriation of EUR 150 million also covers the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, while the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a €50 million contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope primarily as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the project of metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible amendment of the original contract once Hungary has finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment commission.
Bulgaria, a paradise in the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this Balkan country, which has not been mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market that is always the cheapest but will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and low-cost beachfront houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pambrovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are more and more searching for a building in the region of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also awaken the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with commercial and office space promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time seeking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. At the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle in buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and, in general, that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December Bulgaria has been listed as one of the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- or long-term added value.
The price of capital buildings is constantly rising as a result of increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, over the last 5 years, they have increased by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices mainly exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of professionals end on Tuesday, yet Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Road Map, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol's emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there are intense discussions on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, although it was prepared to sign an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 per cent from 1990 levels until 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, excluding emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement has also been signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The Kyoto Protocol aid fund will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the framework of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), reported Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as a flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the level achieved in 1990, regardless of the success of the signing of the "Post-2012 Agreement", and is prepared to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also prepared to make commitments tailored to their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997 the Kyoto Protocol countries had achieved a total reduction of 5.2 per cent, and all 15 EU members of that period made the commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the level of the period 1985 to 1987, and our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be immediately followed by a new international system for reducing emissions, the need for which was stressed in the new report of the IPCC, the international scientific body, which received the UN Nobel Peace Prize in charge of addressing climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided, which scientists believe would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units report, on the video-sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of making themselves popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that was passionate about YouTube: the special units operating in Afghanistan are in charge of video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are monitored at the air force operations headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to Londres where the compatriots charge them on the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air force soldiers have already made 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as Defenceheadquarters in the spring of 2007 and released videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the Air Force's initial objective, the videos were posted on the Internet to recruit and, according to the Ministry of Defence, were also used to inform the general public of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs almost nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, communicated to the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but also inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the merits of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the videos composed and censored carefully, amateur videos have passed through the sharing site which also present, for example, the deaths of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been made on the Internet showing the areas of operation in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been rushing to load these videos.
Americans do the recruitment a little differently by using the America's Army shooting game downloadable for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
