The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganise the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
Parties are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holiday days as well as rest days.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so so that the New Year's Eve can rest quietly.
Moreover, in a year, we have a total of eleven parties marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, in commemoration of the revolution of 1848, as is October 23, which is also the commemoration day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1st is Labour Day, and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember the members of our family and our dead friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
On the days of our state holidays, national or even religious rarely falling on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the party marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a specific regulation on the replacement days of the days preceding or following the holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service companies, institutions that rotate without interruption and in service, because of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year: from December 24th, life stops almost all over the country because according to experiences the majority of people do more overtime or take vacations that they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around the Labour Day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a day of work to have a day of rest on Friday 2 May.
Another change is scheduled for October 23rd: Saturday, October 18th will be a replacement working day on Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year will be marked by parties because from 24 December, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
