This 54-year-old British teacher at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested on Sunday at her home and charged with a violation of Islam and sedition under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints by parents of students to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story goes back in fact to September, when this teacher asks her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear of the class.
"Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed," says the director of the Robert Boulos school.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the bear photo followed by the legend "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself had no label with this name, but the problem is simply the representation of the prophet as an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," he said, "it is only an "innocent mistake."
Opinion shared by many students of the teacher who describe her as "very attentive towards her students" and "who never speaks of religion in the classroom".
