Serbian President Boris Tadic felt that a compromise was still possible, warning the Kosovo Albanian majority against the consequences of a unilateral declaration of the province's independence.
In particular, Belgrade said that it feared a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
"For Serbia," he said, "it does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be taken solely by the Security Council, where its Russian ally has the right of veto.
