It took more than seven hours of space work for astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates at the International Space Station (ISS) to perform the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, which is essential for the continuation of the station's scientific activities.
A risky exit that has accumulated the records because of its duration, its remoteness from the habitable modules, the speed with which it was conceived, tools "crafted" by astronauts to perform the repair.
The problem appeared on Tuesday when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the Shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that was soon to host the European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a kind of dock for laboratory modules.
But we need to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to move a solar panel power generation module weighing 17.5 tonnes, already present on the ISS, to put it on its final position.
After moving it, the crew began the redeployment of the solar panels of the module, which have a wingspan of 76 metres.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfold like accordions, was damaged about a meter by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was stopped to avoid further damage to the panel.
Astronauts, who were originally required to perform a shuttle Discovery control exit, then go and repair another solar panel with a defective rotation system, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to go caracoler at the end of the 30 meters length of the remote control arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to perform the repair.
He is one of the best "spacewalker" of the Nasa.
Large, resistant, very skillful, it has a very developed torso and long arms.
At the age of 46, this trained physician was therefore tasked with "operating" the "injured" solar panel.
After precisely inspecting the damage, he severed the wrong cable and installed some kind of "splints" on the damaged area.
He was assisted by a second "spacewalker" who remained near the airlock and, from the inside, by the other astronauts, including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a hockey mini-cane wrapped in insulation to avoid electrocution on solar panels producing several hundred volts, was designed and "briculated" by astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited until the panel was fully deployed before making an inventory of his tools and returning to the inside of the station.
