The three British bankers who were supposed to testify to their roles in relation to a fraud committed by Enron's previous chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, changed their statement, pleading guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew first declared themselves innocent of the seven charges of alleged collusive fraud committed by Fastow in 2000 in a secret financial scam in order to enrich themselves in spite of their employees.
