They're not Warhols' cases.
The one that connects the Swedish concepts and wooden box, think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Stockholm Type" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" doubted a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the Pontus Hulten museum gave in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as many of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen of "Stockholm Type", which circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting sequence of artistic and curatoric productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given the authorization in 1968 to produce some brick wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not in fact exposed to the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered de jure into the history of art and auction, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Stockholm Type".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hulten museum wrongly claimed that about 100 wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have yielded to him.
In fact, Hulten's 105 cases were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St Petersburg.
At that time, Warhol had already died for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, and then a white oil paint brush was applied.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a layer of background on the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," suggests Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
Already in July the Authentication Board announced, of course, that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, we've had an inexorable silence there.
Manila Rebel Soldiers Abandon
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers abandoned, the same soldiers who had cut themselves off in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the President for electoral corruption and fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
Soldiers loyal to power had shortly before stormed the hotel with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been cut off for hours in the building.
About half of them were in court on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly slip away with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to watch them, had apparently deserted in his favour and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Troops loyal to the government capped the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
The National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have had enough," said Trillanes.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who was in command of the Scout Ranger elite unit, said that other army units soon wanted to join the march.
Critics of the regime called for a major demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila had already been the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurrection broke almost 24 hours after the army refused to join it.
Since 1986 there have been at least seven attempts to putsch against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
